## Phase 0 â€” Discovery

Read whatever is relevant to the current request:
- If extending/auditing: read `2. Tokens` filtered to `Border-Radius` / `Border-Width`.
- If a new stray collection has shown up: inventory it fully â€” name, type, value, scopes, mode
  count per variable. Use `figma_get_variables` with `format: "summary"` first to spot it (it'll
  show up as a 4th+ collection outside the 3 tier names), then `format: "filtered"` +
  `resolveAliases: true` on just that collection for full detail.

**Cross-reference every value against `Scale` by resolved number, not name.** Build the explicit
overlap/gap table. A legacy collection's step naming (e.g. `Radius/050` = `2`) will often already
match a `Scale` step's resolved value even though the variable names differ â€” match on value.

**Flag any value with no Scale match at all** (the historical example: `Radius/Full` = `9999`,
where the nearest Scale candidate `Scale/1000` = `1000` â€” a real mismatch, not a typo). Do not
silently pick a resolution; this is a Gate A decision every time, even though the precedent above
gives a documented "alias to Scale/1000 anyway" default.

## Phase 1 â€” Surface findings (Gate A)

Report, in writing, before proposing structure:
- The full overlap/gap table vs. `Scale`.
- Any value with no match, and the resolution options (alias-with-value-change / create new
  Primitive / literal exception).
- The proposed t-shirt step names for both groups, mapped to the matched Scale steps.
- Whether `none` is being added (state explicitly that it's new, not migrated).

Wait for sign-off before Phase 2.

## Phase 2 â€” Tier 2 build

Use `figma_execute` (no batch/update tool can set `VARIABLE_ALIAS` â€” it isn't a literal value):

```js
const collection = await figma.variables.getVariableCollectionByIdAsync(tokensCollectionId);
// fetch each target Scale primitive by ID with figma.variables.getVariableByIdAsync first
const v = figma.variables.createVariable(`Border-Radius/${step}`, collection, "FLOAT");
v.scopes = ["CORNER_RADIUS"]; // or ["STROKE_FLOAT"] for Border-Width
v.description = `Aliases 1. Primitives > Scale/${scaleStep}`;
for (const modeId of [default, lite, priority, privilege, wealth]) {
  v.setValueForMode(modeId, { type: "VARIABLE_ALIAS", id: scaleVar.id });
}
```

**Gotcha â€” pass the collection object, not its ID.** `figma.variables.createVariable(name, id, type)`
throws `Cannot call createVariable with a collection id in incremental mode. Please pass the
collection node instead.` Always resolve via `getVariableCollectionByIdAsync` first.

Batch all variables (Border-Radius + Border-Width together) in a single `figma_execute` call where
possible â€” cheaper than one call per variable.

## Phase 3 â€” Legacy cleanup

Only runs when migrating a stray collection. Before deleting anything:

1. Walk the entire document (`figma.root.children` â†’ pages â†’ recursive `children`) checking every
   node's `boundVariables` for any of the legacy collection's variable IDs. Don't trust "it's
   probably unused" â€” check.
2. If the scan returns zero matches, confirm with the user, then
   `figma_delete_variable_collection` on the legacy collection ID.
3. If the scan finds bindings, stop. Report the node names/IDs/fields found and do not delete â€”
   those bindings need a rebind plan first (point them at the new Tier 2 variables), which is a
   separate, explicit step requiring its own sign-off.

## Phase 4 â€” Verify

Re-fetch `2. Tokens` filtered to `Border-` with `resolveAliases: true`. Confirm for every
variable, every mode:
- Resolved value matches expectation exactly.
- Every mode (`Default`, `Lite`, `Priority`, `Privilege`, `Wealth`) carries the same alias unless
  Gate A specified otherwise.
- Scopes are `CORNER_RADIUS` / `STROKE_FLOAT`, not `ALL_SCOPES`.

If a legacy collection was migrated, re-fetch the full file summary and confirm only
`1. Primitives`, `2. Tokens`, `3. Semantics` remain.

Report mismatches with variable name + ID â€” never auto-correct silently.

