## Common failure modes

**Passing a collection ID instead of the collection object to `createVariable`.** Throws
immediately. Always `getVariableCollectionByIdAsync` first.

**Assuming a "Full"/"Pill" step's value matches `Scale/1000` without checking.** It may not (see
the `9999` precedent) â€” always verify by resolved value, and treat the mismatch as a Gate A
decision, not something to silently paper over.

**Reverting to pixel-based naming out of habit.** The whole point of this skill is t-shirt sizing
(`sm/md/lg`...) replacing value-based names (`050/100/200`...) from any legacy collection.

**Skipping the live-binding scan before deleting a legacy collection.** Deleting detaches every
bound consumer permanently. Always walk the document first, even if the user says it's fine â€”
report what you actually found.

**Leaving scopes as `ALL_SCOPES`.** Legacy collections may have used it; new Tier 2 variables
should always get explicit `CORNER_RADIUS` / `STROKE_FLOAT` scopes instead.

**Forgetting `none`.** Legacy collections rarely have a zero step; add it by default (aliasing
`Scale/0`) rather than treating it as optional.
